  Fishery production continued to maintain a momentum of 
rapid growth and the output of aquatic products increased by a 
big margin. Aquatic products output was 31,000 tonnes, up 14.8 
percent. 
  The conditions for agricultural production continued to 
improve. By the end of 1993, the total capacity of farm machines 
was 7,331,000 kw, an increase of 0.3 percent; the area of 
effectively irrigated farmland was 1.31 million hectares, an 
increase of 0.8 percent; the amount of chemical fertilizer used 
in farmland (converted into straight products) was 931,000 
tonnes, an increase of 9.9 percent; and the amount of 
electricity consumed in the rural areas was 3.6 billion kwh, an 
increase of 10.4 percent. With the formation and development of 
the rural market economy, the agricultural socialized service 
system in the province was further improved, new achievements 
were made in work "revitalizing agriculture with science and 
technology," and the meteorological departments played a 
positive role in giving guidance to and serving agricultural 
production. 
  The rural economy continued to be vigorous. The output value 
of rural industries, the building industry, transportation, 
commerce, the food industry, and other nonagricultural 
production reached 31.18 billion yuan, up 30.7 percent. The 
output value of these nonagricultural sectors grew at a faster 
rate than that of agriculture and these sectors constituted more 
than half the rural economy, their proportion of the rural 
economy rising from 53.7 to 56.6 percent. In 1993, the turnover 
in rural enterprises was 36.73 billion yuan, an increase of 49.1 
percent, and their net profits were 2.82 billion yuan, up 36.9 
percent. 
<H5>  II. Industry and the Building Industry </H5>
  In 1993, industrial enterprises quickened their pace in 
changing their operational mechanism and their output and sales 
increased simultaneously. The added value of industry was 24.3 
billion yuan, 18.3 percent up, of which industries at or above 
the township level was 18.33 billion yuan, an increase of 14.3 
percent. Nonstate-owned industries developed rapidly and their 
speed of growth was markedly higher than those owned by the 
state. Of the total added value of industry, that of 
state-owned industries increased by 11.0 percent, collective 
industries increased by 27.3 percent (of which industries run by 
villages increased by 30.5 percent), and industries of other 
economic types increased by 14.3 percent. Motivated by 
investment, the growth in heavy industry was faster than that of 
light industry. The added value of heavy industry was 16.1 
billion yuan, 18.6 percent up; and the added value of light 
industry was 8.2 billion yuan, 15.4 percent up. 
  The output of heavy industry products such as the power 
industry, the raw materials industry, the building materials 
industry, and industry for turning out equipment, increased by a 
relatively big margin, while the output of some light industry 
products decreased due to factors such as market demand. 


