<H5>  VI. Foreign Economic Relations </H5>
  In 1993, the province made new progress in opening up to the 
outside world and activities in foreign economic relations 
continued to be vigorous. 
  The momentum of foreign trade was good. In 1993, the total 
volume of imports and exports in foreign trade was $1.49 
billion, 33 percent up. Of this, the total volume of exports 
was $990 million, an increase of 28.6 percent, and the total 
volume of imports was $500 million, an increase of 42.9 percent. 
The reform of the foreign trade structure was further deepened, 
the export commodities structure was optimized, traditional 
export commodities were increased, and the exports field was 
constantly widened. The exports to Hong Kong amounted to $230 
million, 15.7 percent up, those to Japan amounted to $120 
million, an increase of 19.1 percent, and the exports to the 
United State amounted to $70 million, an increase of 17.0 
percent. Foreign-funded enterprises became a new force in 
foreign exchange earning a total of $40 million, an increase of 
28.0 percent. 
  The use of foreign capital increased at a fast rate. In 
1993, new agreements on using foreign capital signed by the 
province involved $920 million, 76.9 percent up. The foreign 
capital actually used amounted to $234 million, an increase of 
360 percent. Foreign businessmen were enthusiastic about making 
investment in Shaanxi and the establishment of a total of 790 
new foreign-funded enterprises was approved, 86.3 percent up. 
  International tourism developed steadily. In 1993, a total 
of 458,000 people visited Shaanxi, 10.4 percent up, among them 
386,000 foreign tourists, an increase of 10.6 percent. Revenue 
from tourism amounted to 500 million yuan in foreign exchange, 
an increase of 22 percent. 
<H5>  VII. Science, Technology, Education, Culture, Sports, and </H5>
Public Health 
  The reform of the science and technology system enhanced the 
continuous emergence of achievements in science and technology. 
In 1993, 420 major achievements in science and technology at 
and above the provincial and ministry levels were made, of which 
90 were in agriculture, 182 in industry, five in the building 
industry, 12 in geological prospecting, 10 in transportation, 
postal services, and telecommunications, 72 in public health, 
seven in education and culture, 26 in scientific research, two 
in finance and insurance, and five in commerce and restaurants. 
If classified according to the levels of the achievements: 
Some 17 were made for the first time in the world or were in 
the world's leading positions, 104 were at the world's advanced 
level, 167 were made for the first time or were in the leading 
positions in China, 117 were at the domestic advanced level, and 
15 were at the advanced level of the province or ministry. In 
addition, 15 science and technology achievements were given 
various kinds of national awards. Patent rights were applied 
for for 2,474 achievements, 14.2 percent up, and 1,941 obtained 
patent rights, an increase of 137.8 percent. 
  By the end of 1993, the total number of professional and 
technical personnel in various fields in local units under the 
ownership of the whole people was 514,000. 
  There are 34 permanent technology markets, 94 centers for 
the 
development and exchange in science and technology. In 1993, 
3,509 transactions involving 400 million yuan were concluded in 
the province's technology markets of the province. 
  In 1993, the province had a total of 67 product quality 
monitoring and testing organs, of which 13 were state testing 
centers. The province formulated and revised 37 
provincial-grade standards of various kinds. 
  Education made new progress in the course of reform. The 
enrollment in ordinary institutions of higher learning increased 
considerably. In 1993, 2,607 postgraduate students were 
enrolled in the province, 551 more than the previous year. The 
number of postgraduate students in school was 6,729, an increase 
of 643. Ordinary institutions of higher learning enrolled 41,556 
undergraduate students and students for special courses, 26.2 
percent up. The number of students in school was 117,307, an 
increase of 16,613. In 1993, the number of students in various 
kinds of secondary vocational schools was 219,000 (including 
62,000 students in technical schools), accounting for 47.0 
percent of the total number of students in senior middle 
schools. The number of students in junior middle schools was 
1,049,000 and students in primary schools totaled 3,978,000. 
The percentage of students among school-age children was 98.4. 
The proportion of graduates from primary schools entering 
schools at a higher level was 83.61 percent, 3 percentage points 
less than the previous year. The student drop-out rates for 
ordinary junior middle schools and primary schools were 9.9 and 
3.1 percent respectively, both higher than the previous year to 
a certain extent. 
  In 1993, institutions of higher learning for adults enrolled 
28,846 undergraduate students and students studying special 
courses and had 62,192 students studying in school, 8,790 and 
10,562 respectively more than the previous year. The number of 
graduates from secondary technical schools for adults was 8,548 
and 1,190,000 students were being trained in technical schools 
for adults. The number of students studying in middle and 
primary schools for adults was 386,000. The number of 
illiterate people was reduced by 192,000. 
  Cultural undertakings flourished. At the end of 1993, there 
were 119 theatrical troupes; 111 cultural halls; 113 public 
libraries; 57 museums; 140 archive storages; 44 broadcasting 
stations at the provincial, prefectural, and county levels; 12 
short- and medium-wave broadcasting transmitting stations and 
relay stations; 11 television stations; 22 television 
transmitting and relay stations with outputs of over 1,000 kw;, 
and 4,018 film projecting units. In 1993, nine feature films 
were produced, 189 new films of various kinds were released, and 
four films were awarded nine grand prizes and six special prizes 
at international and domestic film festivals. The province 
published 445.44 million copies of newspapers, 50.4 million 
copies of magazines, and 168.19 million copies of books. 
  Public health developed favorably. At the end of 1993, there 
were a total of 88,114 hospital beds, 3.5 percent up, and 
123,000 full-time medical and technical personnel, the same 
number as 1992, of whom 59,000 were doctors (including 43,000 
doctors of the Chinese and Western schools) and 29,000 nurses 
and head nurses. 
  New sports achievements were made. In 1993, three athletes 
came first, three second, one third, and two came fourth in 
international competitions; nine athletes came first, 12 second, 
18 third, 16 fourth, 12 fifth, 14 sixth place, 11 seventh, and 
15 came eighth in domestic competitions. Twenty-two athletes 
broke 25 provincial records, one broke a national record, and 
one broke a national record for young athletes. 
<H5>  VIII. Population Growth and People's Living Standards </H5>
  The rate of population growth was controlled to a certain 
extent. According to a sample survey on changes in population in 
Shaanxi in 1993, the birth rate was 17.63 per mill, the death 
rate was 6.55 per mill, and the natural growth rate was 11.08 
per mill. Based on this calculation, the total population of 
Shaanxi at the end of 1993 was 34.425 million, 379,000 more than 
the previous year. 
  The income of the residents increased by a relatively big 
margin. According to a sample survey, the per capita living 
expenses income of urban residents was 1,920 yuan, 23.0 percent 
up and, after allowing for price rises, the actual increase was 
7.9 percent. However, the growth in the income of workers and 
staff members of some enterprises whose operation was 
unsatisfactory was relatively slow. The per capita net income 
of rural residents was 653 yuan, 94.2 yuan up and an increase of 
16.9 percent. After allowing for price rises, the actual 
increase was 6.3 percent. The range of increase has been 
relatively wide in recent years. 
  New achievements were made in the reform of the labor system 
and a labor-employment system is being gradually established. 
In 1993, there were 320 employment agencies at various levels. 
In towns and cities across the province, 166,000 people were 
found jobs. At the end of the year, the proportion of people 
waiting for a job was 3 percent. The labor contract system 
developed considerably and the number of contract workers and 
staff members was 567,000, accounting for 14.4 percent of the 
total number of workers and staff members. Pension and insurance 
under unified plans of the society continued to increase and 
2.022 million workers and staff members and 397,000 retired 
personnel joined such plans. At the end of the year, there were 
3.941 million workers and staff in Shaanxi. The number of 
self-employed laborers and personnel working in private 
enterprises reached 299,000, an increase of 105,000. 
  In 1993, the total volume of wages for workers and staff 
members was 10.5 billion yuan, 10.6 percent up. The annual per 
capita wage of workers and staff members was 2,690 yuan, an 
increase of 10.5 percent. 
  The bank savings deposits by urban and rural residents 
continued to increase. At the end of 1993, the balance of the 
bank savings by residents reached 40.38 billion yuan, 7.28 
billion yuan up or an increase of 22.4 percent. 
  Insurance undertakings developed rapidly. In 1993, the 
total amount of insurance accepted on various kinds of property 
was 81.71 billion yuan, 36.6 percent up. In the whole province, 
10,000 enterprises have their property insured and 3.124 million 
households carrylife insurance. Insurance companies handled a 
total of 62,000 domestic property indemnity cases and paid 280 
million yuan in indemnity. 
  The construction of housing for urban and rural residents 
was 
speeded up. In 1993, 4.09 million square meters of new 
residences were built in towns and cities and 17.55 million 
square meters in the rural areas. 
  Social welfare continued to develop. In 1993, the number of 
beds in various kinds of welfare homes in Shaanxi reached 
15,529, accommodating 11,308 people. In urban and rural areas, 
579,000 people obtained various kinds of social relief. In the 
province, 19.7 percent of townships and towns set up a rural 
social security network. The social service networks of towns 
and cities also developed considerably and 4,532 facilities for 
various social services were built. 
  Environmental protection continued to be strengthened. In 
1993, a total of 2,204 people worked in the environmental 
protection system, with 79 environmental monitoring stations at 
various levels and four nature reserves of national class. In 
the whole year, 84 projects to prevent environmental pollution 
were completed and the total investment in these projects 
amounted to 16.2 million yuan. At the end of 1993, Shaanxi set 
up 52 smoke and dust control zones in 11 cities, with a total 
area of 237 square km, and set up 21 noise pollution control 
zones in nine cities, with a total area of 1.08 square km. 
<H5>  Notes: </H5>
  1. In accordance with the State Council's "Notice Concerning 
the Plan To Implement the New National Economy Accounting 
System" and rules on the new system of forms for reporting 
statistics to the state, relatively great changes have been made 
in the contents and index system in the 1993 communique in order 
to facilitate the overall transition to the new national economy 
accounting system and to guide the economic work to earnestly 
shift to the orbit of improving economic results. The 
communique regards domestic gross output value as the core index 
and does not list indexes such as gross social output value, and 
gross output value of industry and agriculture. 
  2. The gross domestic output value and the added value of 
various industries are the sum total of material products and 
service values usable in final consumption produced or provided 
in a certain country or region in one year. This mainly 
includes values of remuneration for laborers, profits, taxes, 
and depreciation but not transfer values of intermediate energy 
consumption or of raw materials. Therefore, they can more 
comprehensively and truly reflect the fruits of social economic 
activities. The difference between the gross domestic output 
value and the GNP is mainly that the former does not include 
foreign net factor income, but the latter does. 
  Since gross output value includes transfer values such as 
energy consumed and raw materials in the course of production, 
repeatedly calculated factors are many and, therefore, are only 
used for statistics and calculation indexes. For example, the 
total industrial gross output value in 1993 was 81.62 billion 
yuan, as calculated according to ruling prices, and was 75.4 
billion yuan, as calculated according to constant prices of 
1990, 22.4 percent up. The added value of industry was 24.3 
billion yuan, an increase of 18.3 percent. The gross output 
value of agriculture in 1993 was 23.86 billion yuan, as 
calculated according to ruling prices, and 21.78 million yuan, 
as calculated according to constant prices in 1990, 11.5 percent 
up. The added value of agriculture was 13.58 billion yuan, an 
increase of 9.6 percent. 
  3. In the communique, the gross domestic output value and 
various added value indexes for various industries are 
calculated according to ruling prices and the growth rate is 
calculated according to comparable prices. 

